estricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough inflation is much feared for its negative effects on the economy, how to measure it is a matter of considerable debate that has important implications for interest rates, monetary supply, and investment and spending decisions. Underlying many of these issues is the concept of the Cost-of-Living Index (COLI) and its controversial role as the methodological foundation for the Consumer Price Index (CPI). Price Index Concepts and Measurements brings together leading experts to address the many questions involved in conceptualizing and measuring inflation. They evaluate the accuracy of COLI, a Cost-of-Goods Index, and a variety of other methodological frameworks as the bases for consumer price construction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIndexation (Economics)vCongresses. 0aIndexation (Economics)xCongresses. 0aInflation (Finance)vCongresses. 0aInflation (Finance)xCongresses. 0aPrice indexesvCongresses. 0aPrice indexesxCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aBasu, Susanto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradley, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConklin, Jonathan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiewert, W. Erwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiewert, W. Erwin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFeenstra, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernald, John G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFixler, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraumeni, Barbara M., econtributor.4ctb4https:/